>
  <p>
    <strong>gode</strong> (Go Code) is a Go-native TUI coding agent and the event-driven harness
    that powers it. The harness is called <strong>godex</strong>, and it owns the moving parts
    of a coding agent: sessions, tools, workspace state, MCP connections, context
    management, provider adapters, and an event bus that everything else subscribes to.
  </p>

  <p>
    The intent is a clean, extensible base that ML labs and tool builders can use to train,
    evaluate, and run coding agents — without re-implementing the surrounding infrastructure
    every time.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Alpha.</strong> Packages, commands, configuration, event formats, and integration
    points may move, break, or disappear without notice.
  </div>

  <h2>Repository shape</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><code>cmd/gode</code> — CLI entrypoint (TUI, ACP, app-server, resume, version).</li>
    <li><code>internal/godex</code> — event bus, JSONL journal, runner, provider interface, MCP manager, tool registry.</li>
    <li><code>internal/godex/appserver</code> — Codex-style app-server protocol, request handling, transports for desktop control.</li>
    <li><code>internal/godex/tools/builtin</code> — broad initial coding tool set.</li>
    <li><code>internal/tui</code> — Bubble Tea UI with composable Lip Gloss components and view models.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Three ways to drive it</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>TUI</strong> — interactive Bubble Tea interface for humans.</li>
    <li><strong>ACP</strong> — JSON-RPC over stdio for any Agent Client Protocol client.</li>
    <li><strong>App server</strong> — Codex-style JSON-RPC over stdio or WebSocket for desktop integrations.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    All three share the same <code>godex</code> core. The event bus is the seam: every UI,
    transport, and observer is just another subscriber.
  </p>

